14 2. No student shall receive credit for high school graduation
15 more than once for completion of the same unit or set of
16 competencies to satisfy the curriculum requirements of this section.
17 3. A school district shall not be required to offer every
18 course listed in subsections B, C, and D of this section but shall
19 offer sufficient courses to allow a student to meet the graduation
20 requirements during the secondary grade years of the student.
21 L. M. 1. In addition to the curriculum requirements of either
22 subsection B, C, or D of this section, beginning with ninth graders
23 in the 2021-22 2021-2022 school year, in order to graduate from a
24 public high school accredited by the State Board of Education,
Req. No. 3962 Page 19

1 stud ents shall pass the United States naturalization test pursuant
2 to the provisions of this subsection.
3 2. School districts shall offer the United States
4 naturalization test to students at least once per school year,
5 beginning as early as eighth grade at the discretion of the school
6 district; provided, any student may retake the exam upon request,
7 and as often as desired, until earning a passing score. For
8 purposes of this subsection, a passing score shall be 60 out of 100
9 questions.
10 3. School districts shall exempt students with disabilities
11 whose individualized education program (IEP) IEP, consistent with
12 state law, indicates that the student is to be assessed with
13 alternate achievement standards through the OAAP.
14 M. N. For purposes of this section:
15 1. “Contextual methodology” means academic content and skills
16 taught by utilizing real-world problems and projects in a way that
17 helps students understand the application of that knowledge;
18 2. “Locally approved” means approved by the school district
19 board of education;
20 3. “Math-based application course” means a course that teaches
21 math content within a real-world application;
22 4. “Pathway unit” means a course taken by a high school student
23 that is aligned with the student’s current ICAP;
24
Req. No. 3962 Page 20

1 5. “Qualified agricultural education courses” means courses
2 that have been determined by the State Board of Education to offer
3 the sets of competencies for one or more science content areas and
4 which correspond to academic science courses. Qualified
5 agricultural education courses shall include, but are not limited
6 to, Horticulture horticulture, Plant plant and Soil Science soil
7 science, Natural Resources natural resources and Environmental
8 Science environmental science, and Animal Science animal science.
9 The courses shall be taught by teachers certified in agricultural
10 education and comply with all rules of the Oklahoma Department of
11 Career and Technology Education;
12 3. 6. “Rigor” means a level of difficulty that is thorough,
13 exhaustive and accurate and is appropriate for the grade level;
14 7. “Science-based application course” means a course that
15 teaches science content within a real-world application;
16 4. 8. “Sets of competencies” means instruction in those skills
17 and competencies that are specified in the subject matter standards
18 adopted by the State Board of Education and other skills and
19 competencies adopted by the Board, without regard to specified
20 instructional time; and
21 5. 9. “Unit” means a Carnegie Unit as defined by the North
22 Central Association’s Commission on Schools course that meets the
23 equivalent of one hundred twenty (120) clock hours within the school
24 year.
